            &lt;img src=&quot;http://placeimg.com/1000/480/any&quot; /&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;/div&gt;
     &lt;/div&gt;
     &lt;div class=&quot;container&quot;&gt;
       &lt;div class=&quot;row&quot;&gt;
         &lt;div class=&quot;col-md-8 project-name&quot;&gt;
           &lt;h2&gt;
           Project Name
           &lt;/h2&gt;
         &lt;/div&gt;
       &lt;/div&gt;
     &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

**Explanation:**

I&#39;ve created a parent with a class name of `.project` and I&#39;ve set that to have a *position of relative*.

Now, within `.project`, we have the image placed. And also, there is another div with a class name of `.project-name`.

What I am doing with `.project-name` is to make the shape using *borders*, then we make the *height to 0* so that the border collapses onto the h2 inside and then we can **absolutely position it to the bottom** of its parent div.

Go ahead and change those css values to suit your preferred margin lengths, widths and so on.

***EDIT 1:***

You&#39;ve requested that the text *&#39;project name&#39;* has to be wrapped around a div with `.container` class.

I&#39;ve updated the answer accordingly. Please take a look and also notice the following:

 - added a new CSS as `.container` is bootstrap&#39;s global class, its not a good idea to edit it, thus, we reference that particular container by adding `.project .container`. This way, only the `.container` inside a `.project` will get affected, which is what we exactly want to do.
 - The idea is still the same, since the new `.container` which is wrapping the word *&#39;project name&#39;* is inside its parent `.project`, we are again absolutely positioning it to its parent thus, we can just move it all the way to the left.

